*IMPORTANT POST*

Hello Friends,

Our dear friend and musical colleague, Clark Gayton, has suffered a very serious stroke and we are raising money for his rehabilitation. Clark’s community is worldwide, so we have created a GoFundMe page (link in comments below and in bio) as a way to connect the dots. If 1000 people gave $50, that’s all it would take to reach our $50K goal. Perhaps some of you can donate more. Or perhaps less. But anything you can give - even prayers - to help Clark will be a well-spent investment. All proceeds will go to Clark's sister, Cynthia, who is managing his recovery.

We are calling on the community of musicians, club-goers, carousers, and all who have been graced by Clark and his music in the four decades he has roamed, with horn in hand, through New York City dives, esteemed 
venues, street parades, and beyond.

Perhaps you don’t realize that you’re one of those people, but let us assure you: 

If you’ve gone to any NYC music club since 1986…
Or attended big-name stadium concerts…
Or small theaters…
Or passed by a loose jam on a front stoop in the Bronx…
Or you name it...

You have undoubtedly been serenaded at some point by Clark Gayton’s fearless energy and virtuosity. He is omnipresent!

Or maybe you were riding the subway at 2am and noticed a lone musician practicing his trombone at the end of the car. That was Clark just trying to make sure he didn’t wake up his next-door neighbors.

Perhaps the very next night you spotted him on stage at Madison Square Garden with Bruce Springsteen and thought - was that the same guy? - well it was!

And yup that was also him after the MSG show playing sousaphone with a reggae band on the lower-east side until the club rolled down the gate.

This man is the Zelig of all forms of music, namable and unnamable. And what he has given to those of us who love the nightlife and call live music our religion cannot be quantified. If you have the means, please consider a donation for Clark's recovery and thank you for reading.

~ LunÁtico

Rita Lee, a mais completa tradução da força feminina na música brasileira. Lembro daquela vez, quando abri seu show em Petrópolis com o @dadi16 que fazia parte da banda dela na época. Eu, uma menina de 21 anos, começando com essa coisa de ser cantora. Não fui tirar foto, não bati na porta do camarim, eu era meio tímida e não queria incomodar. Eu tava absolutamente radiante com a chance de subir ao palco antes dela e depois só queria mesmo vê-la de perto naquele palco, encantando. E foi aí que no meio do show, depois de cantar vários sucessos, ela disse: “Aquela garota que cantou antes… Alexia, o nome dela. Muito boa, de uma voz forte, interessante. Gostei.” Quem tava do meu lado no gargarejo lembra da minha cara de susto, surpresa, felicidade, êxtase… Eu nem imaginava que ela tivesse me assistido. Essa foi a única vez que vi Rita. Obrigada, rainha. A garota aqui continua cantando, e aquela noite em Petrópolis foi o começo de tudo. ❤️✨ @ritalee_oficial

Hello NYC! We are so excited to see you this week at @lincolncenter ✨

Brazilian-American singer and songwriter Alexia Bomtempo has been heralded by The Washington Post as a "top-shelf Brazilian jazz musician”. She has released five critically acclaimed albums and was recently featured on NPR Music's All Songs Considered. Stéphane San Juan is an internationally recognized French drummer-percussionist and singer-songwriter, having worked with artists such as Amadou & Mariam, Caetano Veloso and Jane Birkin.

Alexia and Stéphane met over a decade ago in the vibrant music scene of Rio de Janeiro. They later reconnected in New York where they began a fruitful musical collaboration that resulted in Alexia’s jazz-meets-bossa-nova album Suspiro. Now based in Brooklyn, they continue to explore and push the boundaries of contemporary songwriting. Their current repertoire is a blend of styles ranging from Brazilian samba jazz to modern French song.

**IMPORTANT POST** (LINK IN BIO)
We are asking everyone to come together for our dear friend and musical colleague @davivieiraofficial whose journey has taken an unexpected turn. If you have been following me here, you know what an inspiring figure Davi has been in my life, not only as an extraordinary musician, but also as a loving friend. Many of you may not be aware of his situation… Davi has developed a severe spinal condition that has led him to undergo 3 (!!) complicated surgeries over the last couple of years - he is now facing a challenging road to recovery. We’ve been awestruck by his perseverance through this difficult period, but the financial burden of his medical treatments and daily living expenses has become overwhelming. Your contribution, no matter the size, will make a tangible impact on his life. Let’s come together as a community to support Davi’s healing journey. Thank you. ❤️‍🩹

#GoFundPapito
